									"text" : "The alea.markov object can be used in many  musical contexts.\n\nChord Progression Generator:\n\nUse a 4-state Markov chain to represent four common chord functions (e.g., I, IV, V, vi).\nSet up transition probabilities that follow common chord progression patterns.\nUse the output to select chords in real-time, creating an ever-evolving progression.\n\nMelody Generator:\n\nCreate a larger Markov chain (e.g., 7 states) representing the degrees of a scale.\nSet transition probabilities to favor certain melodic movements.\nUse the output to generate a melody that follows these probabilistic rules.\n\nRhythm Pattern Selector:\n\nDefine several rhythm patterns and assign each to a state.\nUse the Markov chain to switch between these patterns, creating complex rhythmic variations.\n\nMusical Style Switcher:\n\nAssign different musical styles (e.g., Jazz, Blues, Rock, Classical) to states.\nUse the Markov chain to smoothly transition between styles during a performance.\n\nInstrument/Timbre Selector:\n\nAssign different instruments or timbres to each state.\nUse the Markov chain to orchestrate a piece, changing instrumentation over time.\n\nDynamic Tempo Changes:\n\nAssociate tempo ranges with different states.\nUse the Markov chain to create subtle or dramatic tempo variations.\n\nGenerative Harmony:\n\nUse a larger state space to represent different chord voicings or inversions.\nCreate transition probabilities that favor voice leading rules.\n\nProbabilistic Arpeggiator:\n\nAssign different arpeggio patterns to states.\nUse the Markov chain to switch between patterns, creating complex arpeggios.\n\nDrum Pattern Generator:\n\nAssign different drum hits or short patterns to states.\nUse the Markov chain to generate evolving drum sequences.\n\nMulti-layer Markov Chains:\n\nUse multiple alea.markov objects controlling different aspects of the music (e.g., one for harmony, one for rhythm, one for dynamics).\nCombine their outputs to create complex, multi-dimensional musical structures."
